  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Constructing Component Framework**\n\nI\'ve successfully linked `package.json`, `src/types.ts`, and `server.ts`. Now, I\'m focused on developing the necessary components. I\'m currently creating the component files: `src/components/ChatInterface.tsx`, `src/components/TaskTriageMatrix.tsx`, and `src/components/TimelineBoard.tsx`, and the main file.\n\n\n**Defining UI Structure**\n\nI\'m now structuring the user interface with a split-screen layout in `src/App.tsx`. I\'ve outlined components like `ChatInterface`, `TaskTriageMatrix`, and `TimelineBoard`, each with specific functionalities. Design choices lean towards a modern, minimal aesthetic with light mode using `bg-slate-50` and the default sans-serif font provided by Tailwind, aiming for minimal cognitive load.\n\n\n**Refining Chat Component**\n\nI\'ve just implemented the `ChatInterface` component. It includes state management for input and message history, smooth scrolling to the latest messages, and handles both form submission and Enter key presses (without shift). I also incorporated styling for the header with a title and description, and the main chat area with a light gray border.\n\n\n**Enhancing Chat Interface**\n\nI\'ve been refining the `ChatInterface` to enhance the user experience. I\'ve focused on styling the chat bubbles; user messages use a dark background, while assistant messages are lighter. I\'m also now showing a loading indicator, complete with a triaging message and animated spinner, while I process input. This addition keeps the user informed and engaged during potentially lengthy operations.\n\n\n**Improving Input Handling**\n\nI\'ve just finished the input handling for the `ChatInterface`. I\'ve added a text area for input with a subtle border and rounded corners. There\'s a \"Send\" button that\'s disabled when the input is empty or processing and turns into an enabled state on the presence of text. A submit handler and keyboard press handler are also in place, with the proper icons for clarity and use.\n\n\n**Developing Task Matrix**\n\n\\n\\nI\'m now focusing on the `TaskTriageMatrix` component, splitting tasks into Urgent & Critical, High Dependency, and Micro-Tasks. I\'ve built a modular `Section` component with titles, icons, and item counts to organize each task category. I\'m adding dynamic display with a fallback for empty sections to make the component more user-friendly. The component uses tailwind and react-icons to make it visually clear.\n\n\n**Refining Task Section**\n\nI\'m now integrating task data and interactive elements within the `TaskTriageMatrix`\'s section components. The sections dynamically render task items with titles and estimated time details. I\'ve designed these items with hover effects and styling for clear visual feedback. The empty state has also been addressed and implemented with text and a fallback.\n\n\n**Constructing Timeline Board**\n\nI\'m now building the `TimelineBoard` component to visually represent execution blocks and associated tasks. I\'ve integrated date formatting using `date-fns` for clarity. I\'m handling the empty schedule case gracefully with an informative message and an icon using the lucide-react library. The `TimelineBoard` is responsive and visually clear, using icons to represent block types like break, buffer, or work.\n\n```\n\n**Styling Timeline Blocks**\n\nI\'m now focusing on styling the visual representation of blocks within the timeline. I\'m leveraging Tailwind classes to differentiate block types (break, buffer, work) with distinct colors, icons, and visual cues. I\'m also adding subtle hover effects and a timeline line to enhance clarity and interaction.\n\n\n**Refining Timeline Blocks**\n\nI\'m now putting the finishing touches on the `TimelineBoard` block styling. I\'ve updated the block visual styling. Break, buffer, and work blocks now have distinct colors, with clear icons and cues using Tailwind, and added subtle hover effects. I also added a central timeline line.\n\n\n**Integrating API Communication**\n\nI\'m now integrating the `/api/chat` route to manage communication. I\'ve built a handler for sending messages, with appropriate loading states, and state management. The process includes user message, sending a request to the server, and handling the response for a triaged task set and updated schedule.\n\n\n**Implementing API Handling**\n\nI\'m now implementing the API communication for fetching data. I have built out a complete `try...catch` block with appropriate loading states. I now have the ability to handle both successful responses with task and schedule updates, and API errors, by updating the chat with informative messages.\n\n\n**Finalizing Integration**\n\nI\'m now integrating the completed components, specifically the dashboard and main chat interface, within the application structure. I\'m focusing on their layout, responsiveness, and interaction. I\'ve used responsive layout components to enhance the overall user experience.\n\n\n"
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 57
      nanos: 590286514
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
